  "text": "NATURE PODCAST 28 February 2025 Evidence suggests that risky play provides a wide-range of benefits to children, despite opportunities to do it becoming more restricted than ever. By Benjamin Thompson Julian Nowogrodzki Julian Nowogrodzki is a science writer and editor in Boston, Massachusetts. Benjamin Thompson Download the 28 February long read podcastOver the past two decades, research has emerged showing that opportunities for risky play are crucial for children’s healthy physical, mental and emotional development. However, because play is inherently free-form it has been difficult to study. Now, scientists are using innovative approaches, including virtual reality, to probe the benefits of risky play, and how best to promote it.This is an audio version of our Feature: Why kids need to take more risks — science reveals the benefits of wild, free playNever miss an episode. Subscribe to the Nature Podcast on Apple Podcasts, Spotify, YouTube Music or your favourite podcast app. An RSS feed for the Nature Podcast is available too. doi: https://doi.org/10.1038/d41586-025-00489-2 Related Articles Governments are banning kids from social media: will that protect them from harm? Young people’s mental health is finally getting the attention it needs How to raise a genius: lessons from a 45-year study of super-smart children Subjects Latest on:",
